Description.val:
This line item funds modifications to the A-10 aircraft.  The A-10 is a twin engine, single seat, close air support aircraft capable of delivering a full range of air-to-ground munitions as well as self defense air-to-air missiles.  The primary modification budgeted in FY 14 is the A-10 Wing Replacement modification. The specific modifications budgeted and programmed are below.  

Funding for this exhibit contained in PE 0207131F

Justification.val: Where applicable, justification for individual modifications is provided in the P-3A exhibits.

Description.val:
The Wing Replacement program procures replacement wings for the A-10 because the cost of sustaining A-10 wings has exceeded economic limits. Economic analysis determined a $1.3 billion cost avoidance by replacing wings instead of repairing them. To increase the aircraft service life, replacing A-10 wings with enhanced wing assemblies provides the major contribution to meet the A-10's operational service life requirement. The replacement wings incorporate reliability and maintainability improvements to known fatigue critical locations. With these improvements, the replacement wings do not require major structural inspections for the first 10,000 hours of service life. The replacement wings will be installed as part of the O&M-funded Scheduled Structural Inspections (SSI) to the furthest extent possible.   

Operational Requirement Document: A-10 Multi-Staged Improvement Program, dated 19 Oct 1999.

The President's Budget funds a total of 145 wings. The A-10 fleet was recently restructured to a size of 283 aircraft. Additional funding is required to replace all wings. The current contract supports wing buys through 2016.

Milestone/Development Status

The contractor delivered the First Article in March 2011 and started installation at Hill Air Force Base.  Low Rate Initial Production wing delivery began in 1QFY12 and Full Rate Production wing delivery began 2QFY12.
